II. RELATED WORKS
Jailbreak attacks typically refer to the act of leveraging vulnerabilities within a constrained system (e.g., a large
model) to bypass imposed restrictions and security guardrails, aim to achieve privilege escalation, such as inducing the model to generate a harmful response. In recent times, there has been a plethora of approaches to jailbreak LLMs, which can be roughly categorized into three main types based on the design of prompts: hand-designed approaches [11], [25], model-generation approaches [26], [27], and searchgeneration approaches [20], [28]. With the extensive use of multi-modality data, jailbreak attacks have been developed in the context of LVLMs. Gong et al. [17] divided harmful requests into several steps and presented them as typographic representations in images, requesting the LVLM to complete the blank. Liu et al. [18] employed a text-to-image model to construct visual adversarial prompts by converting harmful textual semantics into images and splicing on typographic images that represent specific textual semantics. In addition, Shayegani et al. [9] constructed adversarial examples and kept the harmful semantics visually hidden. To enhance the probability of the model in generating a specific harmful response, Qi et al. [29] prepared a corpus related to harmful semantics and utilized it to optimize the visual adversarial prompt. Similarly, Niu et al. [30] used a pre-prepared corpus of harmful requests and responses as constraints for optimizing the visual adversarial prompt. Besides jailbreak attacks, another typical way to evaluate the security of models is through adversarial examples [6], [7], [8], [15], [31], [32], [33]. This attack primarily generates inputs containing imperceptible perturbations for deep learning models, aiming to induce model malfunction rather than produce a harmful response. This paper aims to conduct jailbreak attacks on LVLMs to induce harmful responses.
III. PRELIMINARIES
A. Large Vision Language Models
Recent LVLMs (e.g., LLaVA [1], MiniGPT-4 [34], and InstructBLIP [34]) have shown strong performance in a variety of tasks. An LVLM Fθ is typically comprised of three main modules: a visual module Fv (e.g., visual encoder from CLIP [35]), a textual module Ft (usually an LLM such as LLaMA [36] and Vicuna [37]), and a vision-language connector I (e.g., cross attention, projection layer). Given a prompt pair containing a visual prompt (image) xv ∈ V and a textual prompt (text) xt ∈ T, the visual module Fv encodes xv into hv, and the connector I fuses hv with the textual query xt. This fusion process enables the textual module Ft to execute both understanding and generation tasks based on the multimodal features I(hv, xt). To summarize, the LVLM processing flow can be illustrated as
y = Ft(I(hv, xt)), hv = Fv(xv). (1)
Here, we use y = Fθ(xv, xt) for simplicity. Essentially, Fθ is a probability function Fθ : Q → R, where Q = V×T represents the input query domain and R represents the response domain. The response y is generated through predicting the probability distribution p(y|(xv, xt)). Prior to release, developers employ the security alignment techniques [38], [39] on LVLMs to prevent the output of harmful responses y∗ ∈ R.
