C. Comparison With Other Attacks
Our approach distinguishes itself from prior works in several key aspects. Attack motivation. We have meticulously designed perturbations for the dual-modal inputs accepted by LVLM, achieving a more effective and generalizable attack. Similar works [9], [17], [18] primarily focus on constructing adversarial visual images, with limited consideration and careful design of attack effectiveness in the text modality. Attack implementation. Inspired by [11] and [20], we designed visual adversarial prompts using affirmative prefixes and negative suppressions for universal jailbreak, unlike [29] relying on specific harmful content. For textual prompts, we used CoT techniques to guide LLM responses and analyze jailbreak failures, enabling adaptive updates. In contrast, works like [9], [18] rely on manually crafted prompts, lacking systematic optimization. Although [12], [26] perform optimization, [12] relies on predefined logic, authority, and role-playing prompts for LLMs, lacking detailed failure analysis, while [26] employs a computationally intensive branching-and-pruning approach to generate and filter prompt variants. Attack effects. We are the first to implement a universal jailbreak attack in general scenarios, where a single image combined with specific harmful requests can achieve a jailbreak for the corresponding task. In contrast, [29] can only jailbreak harmful speech scenarios, while [12] performs targeted adversarial attacks that prompt the model to output specific words, such as “Unknown”, rather than achieving universal jailbreaking.
V. EXPERIMENT AND EVALUATION
A. Experimental Setups
1) Models and Datasets: In this study, we primarily examine three commonly-used open-source LVLMs including LLaVA [1] (LLaVA-V1.5-7B), MiniGPT-4 [34] (Vicuna 7B), and InstructBLIP [44] (Vicuna 7B). All mentioned models utilize the weights provided by their respective original repositories. Additionally, we evaluate commercial black-box LVLMs, including GPT-4o [2], Gemini [21], ChatGLM [22], Qwen [23], and ERNIE Bot [24]. We employ two commonly used datasets for evaluation: SafetyBench [18] and AdvBench [20]. SafetyBench is a benchmark for evaluating the safety of LVLMs, encompassing 13 prohibited scenarios specified in OpenAI and Meta’s usage strategies [45], [46]. AdvBench [20], widely used in prior LLM jailbreak research, includes 521 harmful behaviors. We eliminated duplicate items from AdvBench and incorporated each item into SafetyBench based on the corresponding scenario for our experiment.
2) Evaluation Metric: We employ Attack Success Rate (ASR) as our primary metric to assess the effectiveness of our approach. ASR quantifies the probability that model Fθ generate a harmful response y∗
t . We followed similar evaluation method [18], [47], [48], [49], focusing on automatic evaluation, and confirmed the results with manual evaluation. Automatic evaluation is conducted using the function J (·) proposed in Sec. IV. For manual evaluation, three volunteers were recruited to verify the responses of the LVLMs. They were provided only with the harmful request and the corresponding scenario as background knowledge, without knowledge of the adversarial prompt pairs. Higher ASRs indicate better attacks. 3) Compared Attacks: We compared BAP with three stateof-the-art jailbreak attacks, including structure-based methods (Liu et al. [18] and FigStep [17]) and an optimization-based method (Qi et al. [29]). Liu et al. combined images related to the attacking intent with typographic text as visual adversarial prompts. FigStep converts harmful instructions into typeset images, paired with neutral text prompts to guide the model to respond. Qi et al. optimized visual adversarial prompts based on a corpus of specific scenarios. Additionally, we report the results of the No Attack scenario, where harmful queries from the dataset are directly fed into the LVLMs. Note that the visual prompts required by all baseline attack methods for each attack are not universal. Liu et al. requires generating images related to the semantics of the harmful instruction using a text-to-image generation model. FigStep reformulates the harmful instruction into a textual statement starting with nouns such as “Steps to”, and subsequently converts this into a typography image as the visual prompt. Qi et al. constructs a specific corpus for optimization based on the different harmful instruction. In contrast, the visual prompts used in BAP are capable of performing universal attacks. Therefore, for a fair comparison, we conducted experiments in both query-dependent and query-agnostic settings in whitebox scenarios. (Since FigStep’s text prompt is entirely neutral and thus ineffective under the query-agnostic setting, we follow its original setup.)
4) Implementation Details: In our BAP, for visual adversarial prompt, we employ 3000-step PGD to optimize Eq. (3), with step-size to 1 and to 32/255. In the text optimization phase, we set the iteration number N = 5, and any textual adversarial prompt obtained after more than 5 iterations is not considered valid, even if it successfully jailbreaks LVLMs. For all evaluated models, we used their default temperature settings. Specifically, we employ ChatGPT to instantiate the LLM M referenced in this paper. All experiments are conducted on an NVIDIA A800 Cluster.
