B. Other Methods for Text Optimization
We conducted an ablation study on the text optimization method itself, keeping the BAP visual perturbation module constant while replacing the text optimization component with advanced LLM jailbreak methods [12], [26]. The results in Tab. IV show that while BAP and its two variants demonstrated varying performance across the 6 evaluated scenarios, BAP achieved the best overall attack effectiveness (average ASR of 63.93%). This is primarily attributed to BAP’s text optimization method being specifically designed to adapt to LVLM responses, enabling step-by-step optimization guidance based on actual LVLM response feedback. Methods like PAIR [12] and TAP [26], as complex search approaches (in our experiments, PAIR required an average of 13.5 iterations, TAP required an average of 9.6 iterations, while BAP only needed 3.2 iterations), can achieve good results in LLM jailbreaking but did not achieve the expected better performance when applied to LVLMs. We believe this is due to the lack of coordination with the visual modality. For PAIR-BAP, which focuses on generating role-based persuasive prompts in pure text environments, this leads to redundant or conflicting content when paired with our adversarial visual prompts. TAP-BAP’s branching strategy generates diverse prompt variants without considering visual modality semantics, resulting in suboptimal prompts or semantic inconsistencies. In contrast, BAP’s text optimization method conducts progressive analysis and semantic guidance with the LVLM’s actual responses, thereby achieving more stable jailbreaking in LVLMs.
