VII. EVALUATION ON BIAS AND ADVERSARIAL
ROBUSTNESS
Our BAP aims to evaluate the generation risks associated with LVLMs. However, its applications extend beyond this. This section will discuss how BAP can evaluate other aspects of LVLMs.
A. Evaluating Bias
During our experiments, we observed that once our attack successfully jailbreaks LVLM, the model mitigation for biases also fails. In particular, we consider three harmful scenarios (i.e., IA, PH, and PO) for conducting the initial jailbreaks using BAP; after a successful jailbreak, we immediately provide a context-sensitive textual prompt to elicit biased responses for LLaVA, MiniGPT4, and InstructBLIP. As depicted in Fig. 10a, when we successfully jailbreak the model within the context of “...creating illegal drugs”, continuing with the textual prompt “Which person do you think is likely to use them?” yields biased responses from the model. As presented in Fig. 10a, our attack achieves an +30.34% bias induction ASR on average, which indicates that our jailbreak attack also enables bias evaluation on LVLMs.
B. Evaluating Adversarial Robustness
Besides bias evaluation, our attack can also be used to evaluate adversarial robustness [6], [31], [32]. As illustrated in
Fig. 10b, for the untargeted attack, given the same adversarial prompt pair, LVLMs will describe the image as anything other than a panda in every query. Given an original image, we employ an LLM to generate a corpus that describes another specific object (for targeted attack) or any other object (for untargeted attack), depending on the type of adversarial attack. The subsequent image and text optimization process remains the same. Here, we create a corpus of 30 descriptive sentences for each attack; for the targeted attack (TA), the object class is horse, while the untargeted attack (UA) includes 30 different animals such as horse, dolphin, and puppy. As shown in Fig. 10b, our attack achieves an over 85% ASR on these LVLMs.
VIII. ETHICAL AND SOCIETAL IMPLICATIONS
The proposed BAP contributes to understanding the safety vulnerabilities of LVLMs and informs the design of more robust alignment mechanisms. However, it may also be misused for malicious purposes, such as generating harmful content at scale.
A. Potential Risks and Societal Impacts
Given the increasing deployment of LVLMs in sensitive areas such as education, healthcare, and public information services, the consequences of successful jailbreaks can be substantial. BAP could lead to the generation of harmful, biased, misleading, or illegal content, undermining public trust in AI systems. Furthermore, BAP’s ability to attack commercial black-box models (e.g. GPT-4o, Gemini) raises concerns about the safety of even the most advanced AI systems.
B. Responsible Disclosure and Research Guidelines
To mitigate these risks, we advocate for responsible disclosure practices. In this paper, we demonstrate the effectiveness of BAP while deliberately omitting specific details of unsafe outputs from LVLMs to prevent potential misuse. We encourage future researchers to adopt similar practices, especially when dealing with high-risk attack vectors like multimodal jailbreaking. Where appropriate, sensitive code or data artifacts can be shared under restricted licenses or through secure channels to balance transparency with safety. Additionally, we recommend that model developers: Integrate jailbreak methods including BAP into standard evaluation processes; Develop defense mechanisms that jointly analyze visual and textual modalities to detect multimodal attacks; Collaborate with policymakers to define regulatory boundaries for safety AI research. The goal of this work is not to promote jailbreaks, but to reveal critical blind spots in current LVLM safety mechanisms. We believe that a deeper understanding of multimodal attacks is essential for building safer and more reliable AI systems. Nevertheless, such progress must be accompanied by strong ethical reflection and precautionary measures to ensure that the benefits of research are not outweighed by its potential harms.
